body:
**Beginner question: not sure if this is an issue with react or with my code. I'm basically asking for help.**

**Current behavior**

I have a property that I pass down to a child component that does not update in real time.

Example:

```ES6
class Parent extends Component {
  state = {
    sampleProp = true
  }
  render() {
    <Fragment>
      <Child sampleProp={this.state.sampleProp} />
      <TouchableOpacity onPress={() => this.setState({sampleProp: sampleProp ? false : true})}>
        {/* button content */}
      </TouchableOpacity>
    </Fragment>
  }
}

const Child = ({sampleProp}) => {
  // some useState hooks
  console.log(sampleProp) // if at this point sample prop is true...

  const onClick = React.useCallback(
    () => {
      console.log(sampleProp) // this is false on first click then true on subsequent clicks
      // update some state
    },
    [stateVariable]
  )

  return (
    <TouchableOpacity onPress={() => onClick()}>
      {/* update some state */}
    </TouchableOpacity>
  )
}
```

Basing from the code above, the value of `sampleProp` in the child component is equal to the one in parent but when I update its value from the parent, then I click on `onClick` from the child, I get the previous value of `sampleProp`. I don't know what I'm doing wrong because I am a beginner with React JS
